Source: Freddie Mac Seller/Servicer Guide  
Section: 8101.4 – Borrower inquiries, Servicing error resolution, audits and access to Mortgage records, Treatment of personal and property information  
Effective Date: 09/10/2025  

Overview

Section 8101.4 establishes requirements for Servicers on how to respond to Borrower inquiries, resolve errors, provide Freddie Mac with access to Mortgage records, and protect personal and property information.

(a) Responding to Borrower Inquiries

Servicers must respond promptly and accurately to Borrower requests regarding their Mortgage.

If the Borrower asks who owns the Mortgage:

Servicer may confirm Freddie Mac ownership after verifying Borrower identity.

If identity cannot be verified over the phone, the request must be made in writing.

Servicer must provide:

Freddie Mac address

Freddie Mac phone number

Freddie Mac loan number

Explanation that the Servicer services the Mortgage for Freddie Mac

If provided verbally, a written follow-up is required.

Freddie Mac Contact (must be provided):

FREDDIE MAC  
8200 JONES BRANCH DR.  
MCLEAN, VA 22102  
800-FREDDIE


Cross-references: 7101.6(b), 7101.7(a), 7101.7(c), 8101.4(d), 8104.1(a).

(b) Error Resolution Procedures

Servicers must investigate and respond to Borrower-asserted Servicing errors.

Borrower written request must include:

Borrower name

Information sufficient to identify the Mortgage file

Statement of the error believed to have occurred

Servicers must:

Have trained staff and policies for tracking and responding to notices of error

Investigate all complaints

Respond with:

Correction notice (with date and Servicer contact info), or

Statement that no error occurred, reasons, Borrower rights, and contact info

Respond within timelines required by law

Maintain documentation in the Mortgage file

Provide files to Freddie Mac upon request

Review internal controls regularly and document findings

(c) Freddie Mac Audits and Access to Mortgage Records
(i) Audit rights

Freddie Mac may audit any Mortgage at any time. Servicers must provide complete files.

(ii) Access to records

Servicer must provide Freddie Mac access to any Mortgage records, including digital systems.

(iii) 30-day delivery timeline

Records must be delivered within 30 days unless Freddie Mac adjusts the deadline.

Failure = violation of Purchase Documents.

(iv) Third-party responsibilities

Servicer must ensure any Servicing Agent or vendor provides Freddie Mac access to all relevant records without notice.

(v) Freddie Mac authority

Freddie Mac may execute documents on the Servicer’s behalf as needed.

Freddie Mac may also monitor Servicer practices related to safeguarding Borrower nonpublic personal information.

(d) Treatment of Personal and Property Information

“Protected Information” includes Borrower data and property information required by law to be confidential.

Servicers must:

Not use Protected Information in ways violating law or creating conflict of interest

Use it only for Servicing Mortgages

Maintain security and confidentiality

Protect against unauthorized access and breaches

Maintain protections even after Servicing rights are terminated

(i) Disclosure of payment history

Servicer must provide Borrower (or authorized third party) with complete, accurate, uncoded payment history upon written request.

(ii) Disclosure of material information

If Mortgage-related information is material to UMBS®, MBS, or WAC ARM PC trading:

Servicer must disclose material information before buying or selling

If disclosure violates law, Servicer must refrain from trading
